\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Lecture 8
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today we will talk about autonomous equations.
 These are differential equations of the form below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=f\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These equations are all separable, but it isn't always easy or possible
 to solve the integrals necessary to solve the equation.
 We can still learn a lot about the solutions by creating a phase diagram
 (also known as a phase portrait).
 To do so, we take the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for all roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These roots are called critical points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a phase diagram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Classify the critical points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When creating a phase diagram, you draw arrows pointing up if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dx}{dt}>0$
\end_inset

 in the region and downward if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dx}{dt}<0$
\end_inset

.
 For a given critical point, if both arrows point toward the critical point,
 then the solution is a 
\series bold
stable
\series default
 solution.
 If both arrows point away from the critical point, then the solution is
 an 
\series bold
unstable
\series default
 solution.
 If some of the arrows point towards the critical point and others point
 away, we say a solution is 
\series bold
semi-stable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Draw a phase diagram, classify all critical points, and sketch solution
 curves for various initial values for 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=\left(x-1\right)\left(x-2\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we will find the critical points:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=0=\left(x-1\right)\left(x-2\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=1,2
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we can draw a phase diagram.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex1a.PNG

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\left(x-1\right)\left(x-2\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)<0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1<x<2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<1$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the directions of the arrows in the diagram.
 As all arrows at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 point away from 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and the arrows at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 all point towards 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 is an unstable critical point and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 is a stable critical point.
 A typical solution curve will move away from unstable critical points and
 towards stable critical points as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Below is a plot of the slope field with some typical solution curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex1b.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Draw a phase diagram, classify all critical points, and sketch solution
 curves for various initial values for 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=x^{2}\left(3-x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we will find the critical points:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=0=x^{2}\left(3-x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0,3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we can draw a phase diagram.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex2a.PNG

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}\left(3-x\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)<0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x<3$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the directions of the arrows in the diagram.
 As all arrows at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

 point towards 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and some of the arrows at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 point towards and away from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=3$
\end_inset

 is an stable critical point and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is a semi-stable critical point.
 A typical solution curve will move away from unstable critical points and
 towards stable critical points as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 For a semi-stable critical point, the solution curve will only move towards
 the critical point on the stable side.
 Below is a plot of the slope field with some typical solution curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex2b.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The logistic equation models population growth.
 Logistic equations are of the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dt}=kP\left(M-P\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $k,M>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a constant related to how quickly a population grows or dies.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the carrying capacity of a population.
 This is the largest population that an ecosystem can support.
 It is possible to solve this equation using separation of variables, but
 the integral involves fairly gross partial fraction decomposition.
 Even without solving the equation, we can find a fair bit about the solution
 by making a phase diagram.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=10$
\end_inset

.
 Then we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dt}=P\left(10-P\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
therefore we have critical points at 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=0,10
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex3a.PNG

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This phase diagram shows a stable solution at 
\begin_inset Formula $P=10$
\end_inset

 and an unstable solution at 
\begin_inset Formula $P=0$
\end_inset

.
 Physically, this means the population will grow to 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 if it is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 and will shrink to 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 if it is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

.
 The model also suggests that a negative population will decrease to negative
 infinity.
 This isn't a physical solution, so we are okay with allowing this.
 We can never have negative population in practice.
 For many species, a population of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 will not allow the population to grow.
 We are okay with this slight inaccuracy in practice, since the model does
 a good job of estimating population for most realistic cases.
 We also see this in the solution curves in the slope field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lecture 8/ex3b.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes we might modify the logistic equation.
 Suppose the population of fish in a pond is currently modeled by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dt}=2P\left(100-P\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is in fish and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is in months.
 Suppose a scientist wishes to add 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 additional fish to the pond each month.
 Then the new model becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dt}=2P\left(100-P\right)+5
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can find the stable population of the pond by finding and classifying
 the critical points of this differential equation.
 First, let's find the critical points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dt}=2P\left(100-P\right)+5=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
200P-2P^{2}+5=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2P^{2}-200P-5=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{200\pm\sqrt{\left(-200\right)^{2}+4*2*5}}{2*2}=\frac{200\pm\sqrt{40000+40}}{4}=\frac{200\pm\sqrt{40040}}{4}=50\pm\frac{\sqrt{10010}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will call these two critical points 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{\pm}=50\pm\frac{\sqrt{10010}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{+}$
\end_inset

 is when we take the 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{-}$
\end_inset

 is when we take the 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

.
 We can see that for 
\begin_inset Formula $P<P_{-}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dP}{dt}<0$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{-}<P<P_{+}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dP}{dt}>0$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $P>P_{+}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dP}{dt}<0$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{-}$
\end_inset

 is unstable and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{+}$
\end_inset

 is a stable.
 This agrees with our intuition.
 We cannot have a negative population of fish.
\end_layout

